03966nam a22005535i 9780822377610DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223776107 a10.1515/97808223776102doi  a(DE-B1597)552048  a(OCoLC)1226680458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN98.R4bF87 1995 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a809.3/9122201 aFurst, Lilian R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAll Is True :bThe Claims and Strategies of Realist Fiction /cLilian R. Furst. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 Truth to Tell -- t2 Let's Pretend ... -- t3 Framing the Fiction -- t4 Not So Long Ago -- t5 The Game of the Name -- t6 Landscapes of Consciousness -- t7 Figuring the Pretense -- t8 The Enactment of Place -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"All is true," realist writers would say of their work, to which critics now respond: All is art and artifice. Offering a new approach to reading nineteenth-century realist fiction, Lilian R. Furst seeks to reconcile these contradictory claims. In doing so, she clarifies the deceptions, appropriations, intentions, and ultimately the power of literary realism.In close textual analyses of works ranging across European and American literature, including paradigmatic texts by Balzac, Flaubert, George Eliot, Zola, Henry James, and Thomas Mann, Furst shows how the handling of time, the presentation of place, and certain narrational strategies have served the realists' claim. She demonstrates how readers today, like those a hundred years ago, are convinced of the authenticity of the created illusion by such means as framing, voice, perspective, and the slippage from metonymy to metaphor. Further, Furst reveals the pains the realists took to conceal these devices, and thus to protect their claim to be employing a simple form. Taking into account both the claims and the covert strategies of these writers, All Is True puts forward an alternative to the conventional polarized reading of the realist text-which emerges here as neither strictly an imitation of an extraneous model nor simply a web of words but a brilliantly complex imbrication of the two.A major statement on one of the most enduring forms in cultural history, this book promises to alter not only our view of realist fiction but our understanding of how we read it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCriticism. 0aFictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRealism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822377610zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822377610423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822377610.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles